did.abstract: Letters to Lucy Prindle Love and Helen Love Scranton, as well as clippings, photographs, and other items

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: The collection is open to researchers by appointment. There are no restricted materials in the collection. Please contact the Special Collections staff to schedule an appointment.
Some of the materials may be stored at the Library's off-campus shelving facility, so researchers should allow at least two business days to have the appropriate boxes paged.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The Love Family Papers were established in the Music Library of Yale University by Helen Scranton's cousin, Mrs. William Gaines, in 1969.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The Love Family Papers are the physical property of the Irving S. Gilmore Music Library of Yale University. Copyrights belong to the composers and authors, or their legal heirs and assigns.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: MSS 1 The Love Family Papers in the Irving S. Gilmore Music Library of Yale University.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: In 4 series as follows: I. Correspondence. II. Miscellaneous Correspondence. III. Printed matter. IV. Photographs.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Love Family Papers consist primarily of letters to Lucy Prindle Love and Helen Love Scranton. The correspondence includes letters from composers, conductors, instrumentalists, singers, and critics. The Papers also contain newspaper clippings, photographs, and miscellaneous items.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Lucy Prindle Love and her daughter Helen Love Scranton played an active role in the social and cultural life of New York in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. Helen Scranton was secretary for many years to Franz Kneisel, the founder of the Kneisel String Quartet. After the dissolution of the Quartet in 1917, she served as secretary to both the Society of the Friends of Music and the Beethoven Association of New York.
